From BBCLearningEnglish.com

3
00:00:08.240 --> 00:00:11.800
Hello, this is 6-Minute English from BBCLearningEnglish.

4
00:00:11.800 --> 00:00:12.600
I'm Neil

5
00:00:12.600 --> 00:00:13.800
And I'm Beth.

6
00:00:13.800 --> 00:00:17.000
Neil, what is the oldest thing you have at home?

7
00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:21.800
Oh, well, I do have some books from when I was a child.

8
00:00:21.800 --> 00:00:26.000
I have a rocking horse that was my dad's, so that is quite old.

9
00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:33.000
But, neither of these are anywhere near as old as the 1800 year old Roman coin,

10
00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:37.600
which BBC reporter Ryan Keen recently bought in London.

11
00:00:37.600 --> 00:00:41.400
But soon afterwards, Ryan discovered there was more to the story,

12
00:00:41.400 --> 00:00:46.000
as he explains here on BBC World Service Program Business Daily.

13
00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:50.000
But as I researched into other kinds of engine artifacts, I could acquire.

14
00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:55.200
I came across reports of expansive criminal networks related to antiquities.

15
00:00:55.200 --> 00:01:00.800
Some ancient artifacts being sold online and in stores have been looted and traffic.

16
00:01:00.800 --> 00:01:05.200
Ryan got interested in artifacts from Egypt, Greece and Rome.

17
00:01:05.200 --> 00:01:11.600
An artifact is any object made by humans, usually very old, which is historically interesting,

18
00:01:11.600 --> 00:01:13.600
for example, a coin or statue.

19
00:01:13.600 --> 00:01:19.000
In the past, many artifacts have been looted or stolen by force.

20
00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:24.200
Movies, like Indiana Jones and Tomb Raider, have made the subject popular.

21
00:01:24.200 --> 00:01:29.600
But the theft of ancient objects is a serious problem in some parts of the world.

22
00:01:29.600 --> 00:01:31.800
So what can be done about it?

23
00:01:31.800 --> 00:01:36.800
That's what we'll be discussing in this episode, using some useful new words and phrases.

24
00:01:36.800 --> 00:01:43.400
And remember, you'll find all the vocabulary from this episode on our website, BBCLearningEnglish.com.

25
00:01:43.400 --> 00:01:45.600
Now I have a question for you, Beth.

26
00:01:45.600 --> 00:01:51.400
One of the most famous ancient artifacts was discovered by Egyptologist Howard Carter

27
00:01:51.600 --> 00:01:54.600
in the Valley of the Kings in 1922.

28
00:01:54.600 --> 00:01:56.600
But what was it?

29
00:01:56.600 --> 00:02:03.200
Was it A, the Resetta Stone, B, the Mask of Tutankhamun, or C, the Ark of the Covenant?

30
00:02:03.200 --> 00:02:06.600
Oh, I think it's B, the Mask of Tutankhamun.

31
00:02:06.600 --> 00:02:10.000
Okay, let's find out later in the program.

32
00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:12.800
Stealing ancient objects is nothing new.

33
00:02:12.800 --> 00:02:17.800
During colonial times, it was common for artifacts to be taken from their original home

34
00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:21.600
and moved to museums and private collections abroad.

35
00:02:21.600 --> 00:02:26.800
In the modern era, technology, especially social media, has increased the problem.

36
00:02:26.800 --> 00:02:32.400
Here's Amma Al-Azam, a researcher from Shawnee State University in the US, explaining more

37
00:02:32.400 --> 00:02:34.800
to BBC's business daily.

38
00:02:34.800 --> 00:02:38.400
Social media is the game changer here.

39
00:02:38.400 --> 00:02:43.000
The bottleneck, if you will, was, how does someone who has an item then communicate

40
00:02:43.400 --> 00:02:45.200
with someone on the demand side?

41
00:02:45.200 --> 00:02:49.800
It used to slow the process you had to go through into media, so shall media changes

42
00:02:49.800 --> 00:02:52.200
all that, because it just opens it up.

43
00:02:52.200 --> 00:02:58.400
Amma calls social media a game changer, something new that is introduced into a situation

44
00:02:58.400 --> 00:03:01.200
and completely changes how it works.

45
00:03:01.200 --> 00:03:05.600
For example, the internet has been a game changer in how we communicate.

46
00:03:05.600 --> 00:03:07.400
The reason is simple.

47
00:03:07.400 --> 00:03:12.800
For someone with illegally stolen artifacts to sell, finding a buyer used to be difficult.

48
00:03:13.200 --> 00:03:19.000
Amma thinks that now, because of social media, this problem or bottleneck is gone.

49
00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:24.000
A bottleneck is a problem that delays a process or stops it from progressing.

50
00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:29.600
So what can be done to stop the illegal buying and selling of ancient artifacts?

51
00:03:29.600 --> 00:03:36.800
Well, as the final destination for much-alluted treasure, museums have an important role to play.

52
00:03:37.200 --> 00:03:44.200
Accusations of knowingly or unknowingly buying stolen objects have been made against several museums,

53
00:03:44.200 --> 00:03:46.400
including the Louvre in Paris.

54
00:03:46.400 --> 00:03:51.400
Victoria Reed is senior curator at the Museum of Fine Arts in Boston.

55
00:03:51.400 --> 00:03:59.400
In 2024, she helped her museum return an ancient necklace, which had been taken illegally from Turkey in the 1970s.

56
00:03:59.400 --> 00:04:06.400
But the idea of returning artifacts to their country of origin, something known as repatriation, is controversial.

57
00:04:06.400 --> 00:04:10.400
As Victoria told BBC Program Business Daily.

58
00:04:10.400 --> 00:04:18.400
Outside of the Museum, we're all of course, there are many opinions, and I personally try to maintain a relatively middle of the road approach.

59
00:04:18.400 --> 00:04:20.400
I believe in museums.

60
00:04:20.400 --> 00:04:26.200
I believe in responsible collecting, and I believe in judicious repatriation decisions.

61
00:04:26.200 --> 00:04:31.200
There are arguments both full and against repatriating artifacts.

62
00:04:31.200 --> 00:04:34.400
And Victoria takes a middle of the road approach.

63
00:04:34.400 --> 00:04:41.200
If you describe something as middle of the road, you mean it's not extreme and is acceptable to most people.

64
00:04:41.200 --> 00:04:48.600
Whether ancient artifacts find their way back to their original homes, or are displayed in museums, remains an ongoing debate.

65
00:04:48.600 --> 00:04:55.000
But either way, it's good to know that objects of culture and beauty are being preserved for future generations.

66
00:04:55.000 --> 00:04:58.400
Okay, I think it's time to reveal the answer to my question.

67
00:04:58.400 --> 00:05:05.400
I asked what the Egyptologist Howard Carter discovered in the Valley of the Kings in 1922.

68
00:05:05.400 --> 00:05:11.400
Was it A, the Rosetta Stone, B, the Mask of Tutanakamun, or C, the Ark of the Covenant?

69
00:05:11.400 --> 00:05:14.000
And I said the Mask of Tutanakamun.

70
00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:16.000
And you, Beth, were right.

71
00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:17.000
Yes.

72
00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:21.800
Okay, let's recap the vocabulary we've learned, starting with Artifact.

73
00:05:21.800 --> 00:05:26.000
Any object made by humans, which is of historical interest.

74
00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:29.400
If something is looted, it's stolen by force.

75
00:05:29.400 --> 00:05:35.600
A game changer is a new element, which, when introduced into a situation, completely changes it.

76
00:05:35.600 --> 00:05:41.000
A bottleneck is a problem that delays a process or stops it from progressing.

77
00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:45.000
To repatriate something means to return it to the country, it came from.

78
00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:53.000
And finally, the adjective middle of the road describes things which are not extreme and are acceptable to most people.

79
00:05:53.000 --> 00:05:55.400
Once again, our six minutes are up.

80
